+\begin{remark}[Stability vs.\ existence vs.\ uniqueness]
+\label{rem:stab_vs_unique}
+Theorem~\ref{thm:stab123} establishes \emph{unconditional} energy
+stability for Scheme~II: it holds for all $\ddt>0$ and all $h>0$.
+Existence and uniqueness, however, both require time-step
+restrictions because the nonlinear T2 term in Scheme~II couples
+$(\bU^k,\bM^k)$ at the current time level.
+\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
+\item \emph{Existence} (Theorem~\ref{thm:exist_II}) requires
+$\ddt\le\tau_*(h,R)=(2\widetilde{C}^2)^{-1}\,h^d\,R^{-2}$,
+arising from the absorbing-ball self-mapping argument.
+In two dimensions this is a parabolic-type CFL,
+$\tau_*\sim h^2/R^2$, which is the standard restriction one
+expects for a fully nonlinear Brouwer fixed-point construction.
+\item \emph{Uniqueness} (Theorem~\ref{thm:unique_II}) requires
+$\ddt<\tau_0=C_*^{-2/3}\sim h^{2/3}/R^{2/3}$,
+arising from a contractivity argument for the difference of two
+solutions.
+\end{itemize}
+For typical data with $R\ge\sqrt{2}$ and $h\ll R$, one has
+$\tau_*\ll\tau_0$, so the existence-CFL is the binding constraint
+in practice; whenever existence is achieved, uniqueness is
+automatic.
+
+Both restrictions depend on the mesh and the energy level, and are
+typically far below accuracy-driven time steps.
+For Scheme~I, neither condition is needed: the fully explicit
 T2 term makes the system linear and unconditionally uniquely
